Based on recent reporting that offers conflicting reports of OPEC+ either extending cuts past June or evaluating the cuts and increasing production in July I will stick with a prediction similar to last week. Based on March 2020's OPEC Crude oil production based on direct communication combined with OPEC crude oil production based on secondary sources which are 26,275 tb/d and 28,612 tb/d respectively. In conjunction with the metrics above, open source information has OPEC countries cutting production for April and the following months. With that said I predict the production to be cut between 10-20% resulting in a range of 22,400 to 25,200 TB/d.

Compliance is not perfect among the OPEC states [1]. ~4.48 million bpd of the pledged reduction have been done ~74% of the agreed cuts. OPEC (without countries from OPEC+) have pumped 24.77 million barrels per day (bpd) this month. OPEC's share amounts to 6.084 million bpd. Saudi Arabia announced back in April that the cuts will be effectively ~12.5 million bpd as they plan to reduce production even more than under the OPEC agreement [2]. This means OPEC would effectively cut by ~8.8 million bpd assuming OPEC+ countries cut by ~3.6 million bpd. OPEC oil production was ~30 million bpd in April [3].

The current oil production by OPEC is about 24,000 tb/day. As per the April 21 news, the OPEC has agreed a deal to reduce it by 10,000 tb/day. Going by this, it will be 14,000 tb/day in May 2020. However, if countries begin to ease transportation, build inventories, etc, there are chances that the production could be increased by 50% from the May level, which means that the production will be 21,000 tb/day at June end. Hence, OPEC production forecast is between 14,000 - 21,000 tb/day at end-June 2020.

OPEC has stated that they intend to cut 9m b/d off production in April, which would put them somewhere between 18-19m b/d. However, their members typically agree to lower production targets and then don't cut their production by as much as they agreed to, making it likely that the total production will be less than 27m b/d but higher than the 18-19m b/d target that was announced for April-May. It seems likely that by June production will be in the 20-24m b/d range.

This one is hard. The primary difficulty comes in estimating how much of the 9.7mb/d production cut will be absorbed by OPEC (rather than OPEC+ and/or remaining oil producers). If OPEC takes 60% of that 9.7mb/d (a common estimate), then we should expect to see a 24mb/d output in June, which as we can see is strategically placed as an answer partition. Consequently, my estimate between these two partitions is relatively close. If this were my report, I would likely modify the ranges so as to increase my confidence level. That is, I could claim with, say, 62% certainty that tb/d for OPEC would be between 22,500 and 25,500mb/d, thereby keeping the 3mb/d increments, but increasing the confidence level.
